Author-Name:  Lowrey, Tina M
Author-Name:  Shrum, L J
Title: 
 Toward an Understanding of Consumer Ambivalence.

Journal: Journal of Consumer Research
Pages: 80-93
Issue: 1
Volume: 24
Year: 1997
Month:  June 
Abstract:

 A case study of wedding planning is used to explore the concept of
 consumer ambivalence. Focus groups, in-depth interviews, and shopping
 trips were employed to generate text. A formal definition of consumer
 ambivalence is provided. Our analysis revealed four antecedents of
 consumer ambivalence: expectation versus reality, overload, role conflict
 with purchase influences, and custom and value conflict. These antecedents
 were then linked to particular coping strategies that informants employed
 to manage the ambivalence that was generated. Suggestions of how future
 research might explore consumer ambivalence are offered.


