Author-Name:   Sen, Sankar
Author-Name:  Johnson, Eric J
Title: 
 Mere-Possession Effects without Possession in Consumer Choice.

Journal: Journal of Consumer Research
Pages: 105-17
Issue: 1
Volume: 24
Year: 1997
Month:  June 
Abstract:

 In this article we examine whether and why preferences for a good
 produced by its mere and arbitrary possession (i.e., a mere-possession
 effect) occurs even in the absence of actual possession. In two
 experiments, we demonstrate that merely possessing a coupon for a product,
 as opposed to the actual product, can increase consumers' preference for
 that option over its competitors' in real choices from meaningfully
 comparable choice sets. In addition, a characterization of the cognitive
 processes underlying this phenomenon, and its variation with individual
 perceptions of task meaningfulness, provides support for a loss-aversion
 account of consumers' possession-induced preferences for goods they do not
 actually possess.


